(
<figureCitation id="4CEE44D6CE27FF87FF53B5C0FEA7FD46" box="[201,330,646,671]" captionStart="Figures 1–7" captionStartId="6.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[242,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[241,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 1–7. Xysma dominicum Antropov. 1–2) Face (in frontal view). 1) Female. 2) Male. 3) Mesosoma of the male (in dorsal view). 4–5) Habitus images. 4) Female. 5) Male. 6) Illustrations of the fore- and hindwings. 7) Emerged cocoons obtained from nests." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3674911" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3674911/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 1, 4, 6</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9CCF0BD8CE27FF87FF5AB5F0FCFFFB0B" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="description">
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE27FF87FF5AB5F0FAC5FD17" blockId="3.[192,1441,694,1235]" box="[192,1320,694,719]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FF5AB5F0FDC9FD16" bold="true" box="[192,548,694,719]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Description of the female.</emphasis>
Body length 2.6–3.0 mm. Fore wing length 
<quantity id="132DF5B6CE27FF87FBA1B5F1FB27FD16" box="[1083,1226,695,719]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" unit="mm" value="1.6" valueMax="1.7" valueMin="1.5">1.5–1.7 mm</quantity>
(
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FB40B5F1FB07FD16" box="[1242,1258,695,718]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">n</emphasis>
= 5).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE27FF87FF72B591FE95FC88" blockId="3.[192,1441,694,1235]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FF72B591FE11FD37" box="[232,508,727,751]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Integument coloration.</emphasis>
Black except the following areas yellow: flagellum, clypeus, mandible except apex, propleuron, pronotum, pronotal lobe, legs, including coxae; and tegula. Some terga and sterna laterally and apically reddish brown. Wings clear, hyaline throughout, veins pale yellow, stigma light reddish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE27FF87FF72B41EFC93FC48" blockId="3.[192,1441,694,1235]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FF72B41EFE9AFCA8" box="[232,375,856,880]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Pubescence.</emphasis>
Inconspicuous; with scattered short pale hairs throughout, densest on mandibles, legs, and posterior metasomal segments, especially T5 and T6.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE27FF87FF72B4DEFA9AFBAA" blockId="3.[192,1441,694,1235]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FF72B4DEFE27FC68" box="[232,458,920,944]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Surface sculpture.</emphasis>
Weak except propodeum strongly sculptured. Frons, vertex, gena, pronotum, mesoscutum, scutellum, metanotum, and mesepisternum coriaceous. Gena with scattered, irregular punctures. Basal area of propodeum with striae diverging laterally; two parallel longitudinal carinulae enclosing short transverse parallel striae medially; striated laterally with subparalled striae, some of which extend to the lateral margin of the propodeum (
<figureCitation id="4CEE44D6CE27FF87FCFBB35CFC25FBEA" box="[865,968,1050,1074]" captionStart="Figures 1–7" captionStartId="6.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[242,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[241,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 1–7. Xysma dominicum Antropov. 1–2) Face (in frontal view). 1) Female. 2) Male. 3) Mesosoma of the male (in dorsal view). 4–5) Habitus images. 4) Female. 5) Male. 6) Illustrations of the fore- and hindwings. 7) Emerged cocoons obtained from nests." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3674911" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3674911/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 3, 5</figureCitation>
). Posterior surface of propodeum with median groove, laterally striated, some branched; mostly coriaceous towards the ventral area. First tergum polished; terga microstriate or microcoriaceous, micropunctate. Sterna shiny and glabrous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE27FF87FF72B33DFCFFFB0B" blockId="3.[192,1441,694,1235]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FF72B33DFE8EFB4A" box="[232,355,1147,1170]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Structure.</emphasis>
Medial clypeal lobe convex with broad apical emargination; inner eye orbits slightly converging above; vertex prominent. Gena slightly broader than eye. Front legs with spines of tarsus not forming tarsal rake. Wings venation as in 
<figureCitation id="4CEE44D6CE27FF87FD5CB3FDFCE2FB0B" box="[710,783,1211,1235]" captionStart="Figures 1–7" captionStartId="6.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[242,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[241,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 1–7. Xysma dominicum Antropov. 1–2) Face (in frontal view). 1) Female. 2) Male. 3) Mesosoma of the male (in dorsal view). 4–5) Habitus images. 4) Female. 5) Male. 6) Illustrations of the fore- and hindwings. 7) Emerged cocoons obtained from nests." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3674911" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3674911/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9CCF0BD8CE27FF87FF5AB3ADFCCAFA3E" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE27FF87FF5AB3ADFCCAFA3E" blockId="3.[192,1440,1259,1510]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FF5AB3ADFE19FADB" bold="true" box="[192,500,1259,1283]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE27FF87FE66B3AAFD0CFADB" box="[508,737,1259,1283]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dominicum">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FE66B3AAFD0CFADB" box="[508,737,1259,1283]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Xysma dominicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more closely related to Central American species than to the North American species [
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE27FF87FDA5B24AFCB9FAFC" authority="(Viereck)" baseAuthorityName="Viereck" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[575,852,1291,1316]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceanothae">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FDA5B24AFD34FAFB" box="[575,729,1291,1315]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">X. ceanothae</emphasis>
(Viereck)
</taxonomicName>
]. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE27FF87FB8FB24AFB42FAFB" baseAuthorityName="Viereck" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[1045,1199,1291,1315]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceanothae">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FB8FB24AFB42FAFB" box="[1045,1199,1291,1315]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">X. ceanothae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
through its densely sculptured head and mesosoma, longer pronotal collar, and basal area of propodeum without a longitudinal medial carina. 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE27FF87FE25B20BFC53FABC" authority="Antropov and Cambra" authorityName="Antropov and Cambra" authorityYear="2003" box="[447,958,1356,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="panamense">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FE25B20BFD4EFABC" box="[447,675,1357,1380]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Xysma panamense</emphasis>
Antropov and Cambra
</taxonomicName>
has the pronotal collar not emarginate medially, the basal area of propodeum with weaker striate lateral portions, and the carina bordering the propodeal posterior side is dorsally interrupted. Conversely, in 
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FC65B2CBFB59FA7D" box="[1023,1204,1421,1445]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE27FF87FC65B2CBFB42FA7D" box="[1023,1199,1421,1445]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dominicum">X. dominicum</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the pronotal collar emarginates, has stronger striate lateral portions in the basal area of propodeum, and the carina bordering the propodeal posterior side is entire, dorsally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSection id="BD5A41B8CE27FF87FF5AB15BFCCDF851" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="multiple">
<subSubSection id="9CCF0BD8CE27FF87FF5AB15BFE05F93F" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE27FF87FF5AB15BFC74F9ED" blockId="3.[192,921,1565,1590]" box="[192,921,1565,1590]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<heading id="8F22EF3FCE27FF87FF5AB15BFC74F9ED" bold="true" box="[192,921,1565,1590]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FF5AB15BFC74F9ED" bold="true" box="[192,921,1565,1590]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
Association of female with male of 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE27FF87FD05B158FC74F9ED" box="[671,921,1565,1589]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dominicum">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE27FF87FD05B158FC74F9ED" bold="true" box="[671,921,1565,1589]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Xysma dominicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE27FF87FF72B108FBC5F9BE" blockId="3.[192,1440,1614,1768]" box="[232,1064,1614,1638]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
Male body length 
<quantity id="132DF5B6CE27FF87FE59B108FDCEF9BE" box="[451,547,1614,1638]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" unit="mm" value="2.7">2.7 mm</quantity>
. Forewing length 
<quantity id="132DF5B6CE27FF87FD64B108FCB4F9BE" box="[766,857,1614,1638]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" unit="mm" value="1.7">1.7 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation id="4CEE44D6CE27FF87FCF0B108FBF7F9BE" box="[874,1050,1614,1638]" captionStart="Figures 1–7" captionStartId="6.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[242,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[241,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 1–7. Xysma dominicum Antropov. 1–2) Face (in frontal view). 1) Female. 2) Male. 3) Mesosoma of the male (in dorsal view). 4–5) Habitus images. 4) Female. 5) Male. 6) Illustrations of the fore- and hindwings. 7) Emerged cocoons obtained from nests." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3674911" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3674911/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 2, 3 and 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE27FF87FF72B129FE05F93F" blockId="3.[192,1440,1614,1768]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
In terms of secondary sexual characteristics, females differ from males most notably in that only the clypeus of the face is yellow (
<figureCitation id="4CEE44D6CE27FF87FDBEB1C9FD85F97F" box="[548,616,1679,1703]" captionStart="Figures 1–7" captionStartId="6.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[242,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[241,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 1–7. Xysma dominicum Antropov. 1–2) Face (in frontal view). 1) Female. 2) Male. 3) Mesosoma of the male (in dorsal view). 4–5) Habitus images. 4) Female. 5) Male. 6) Illustrations of the fore- and hindwings. 7) Emerged cocoons obtained from nests." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3674911" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3674911/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), whereas in males the entire lower half of the face and genal area are yellow (
<figureCitation id="4CEE44D6CE27FF87FED0B1E9FE46F91F" box="[330,427,1711,1735]" captionStart="Figures 1–7" captionStartId="6.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[242,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[241,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 1–7. Xysma dominicum Antropov. 1–2) Face (in frontal view). 1) Female. 2) Male. 3) Mesosoma of the male (in dorsal view). 4–5) Habitus images. 4) Female. 5) Male. 6) Illustrations of the fore- and hindwings. 7) Emerged cocoons obtained from nests." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3674911" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3674911/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 2, 5</figureCitation>
). Males have 13 antennal segments (females with 12) and seven exposed metasomal terga (females with six).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
