<subSection id="BD5A41B8CE20FF80FF5AB79FFC69FBBC" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="multiple">
<subSubSection id="9CCF0BD8CE20FF80FF5AB79FFC69FBBC" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE20FF80FF5AB79FFE40FF29" blockId="4.[192,429,217,241]" box="[192,429,217,241]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<heading id="8F22EF3FCE20FF80FF5AB79FFE40FF29" bold="true" box="[192,429,217,241]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE20FF80FF5AB79FFE40FF29" bold="true" box="[192,429,217,241]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Nesting behavior</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE20FF80FF72B64CFD18FEB9" blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
The nests were built in a shaded vertical bank, consisting of a white clay-like substrate, which was very loose. Other 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FE00B66CFDA8FE9A" box="[410,581,298,322]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
, including the bees 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FCA1B66FFB56FE9A" authority="(Fabricius)" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[827,1211,297,322]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Anthophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tricolor">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE20FF80FCA1B66FFBC0FE99" box="[827,1069,297,321]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Anthophora tricolor</emphasis>
(Fabricius)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FB60B66FFA4DFE99" box="[1274,1440,297,321]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE20FF80FB60B66FFA4DFE99" box="[1274,1440,297,321]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Lasioglossum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. and the wasp 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FE0FB60CFE3DFEB9" box="[405,464,330,353]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Liris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE20FF80FE0FB60CFE3DFEB9" box="[405,464,330,353]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Liris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp., nested in this area.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE20FF80FF72B62CFB6BFDDA" blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
Females of 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FEE2B62CFE26FE59" authorityName="Pate" authorityYear="1937" box="[376,459,362,385]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE20FF80FEE2B62CFE26FE59" box="[376,459,362,385]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Xysma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
constantly overflew the nesting area, keeping their body almost vertical (with the metasoma down), with zigzag movements before entering the nest. They generally landed a few centimeters from the entrance before walking inside, although at other times they flew in directly. The females remained inside the nests when resting and perhaps during the night. There was internal closure, made with soil, during the time that females remained inside the nest.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE20FF80FF72B54CFAE3FD9A" blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Females grabbed the prey with their mandibles, holding them by one of the forelegs or neck, with the ventral region facing upwards. The prey consisted of immature thrips (Thysanoptera).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE20FF80FF72B50DFC11FD1B" blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
The average diameter of the entrance was 
<quantity id="132DF5B6CE20FF80FD64B50CFCB7FDBA" box="[766,858,586,610]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
(n=8, range=2.0– 
<quantity id="132DF5B6CE20FF80FBAFB50DFB78FDBA" box="[1077,1173,587,611]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.2 mm</quantity>
, SD=0.5). Nests were short, with an approximate depth of 
<quantity id="132DF5B6CE20FF80FDE5B52DFD55FD5A" box="[639,696,619,643]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
(n=4), with the entrance on the same plane as the substrate. The absence of a foretarsal rake and pygidial plate means that females are poorly equipped for digging, but in this case the friable substrate perhaps facilitated excavation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE20FF80FF72B58AFBD2FC9B" blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
Due to a shortage of time and the difficulty of digging in this substrate, little attention was paid to the excavation of the nests without knowing the number of cells they possibly contained. Cocoons were stuck to the substrate, and usually observed attached together (in twos, threes and sometimes fours) (
<figureCitation id="4CEE44D6CE20FF80FF53B46DFEFCFC9B" box="[201,273,811,835]" captionStart="Figures 1–7" captionStartId="6.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[242,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[241,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 1–7. Xysma dominicum Antropov. 1–2) Face (in frontal view). 1) Female. 2) Male. 3) Mesosoma of the male (in dorsal view). 4–5) Habitus images. 4) Female. 5) Male. 6) Illustrations of the fore- and hindwings. 7) Emerged cocoons obtained from nests." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3674911" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3674911/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Cocoon size ranged from 
<quantity id="132DF5B6CE20FF80FDC2B46DFD13FC9B" box="[600,766,811,835]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.95" metricValueMax="3.1" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" unit="mm" value="2.95" valueMax="3.1" valueMin="2.8">2.8 to 3.1 mm</quantity>
(x=3.0 mm, SD=0.1, n=5).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE20FF80FF72B40AFC66FC7C" blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
It seems that the females covered the cells with some substance, likely silk; it is known that other members of the subtribe 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FE77B42AFD66FC5C" authorityName="Menke" authorityYear="1989" box="[493,651,876,900]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Spilomenina">Spilomenina</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FD0FB42DFC79FC5C" authority="Shuckard" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1838" box="[661,916,875,900]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Spilomena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE20FF80FD0FB42DFCF5FC5B" box="[661,792,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Spilomena</emphasis>
Shuckard
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FC38B42DFB52FC5C" authority="F. Smith" authorityName="F. Smith" box="[930,1215,875,900]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Arpactophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE20FF80FC38B42DFBA3FC5B" box="[930,1102,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Arpactophilus</emphasis>
F. Smith
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FB60B42AFEE3FC7C" authority="Ducke" authorityName="Ducke" authorityYear="1907" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Microstigmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE20FF80FB60B42AFA4DFC5B" box="[1274,1440,876,899]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Microstigmus</emphasis>
Ducke
</taxonomicName>
use silk in nesting (
<bibRefCitation id="B04425A2CE20FF80FD9EB4CAFC93FC7C" author="Matthews, R. W. &amp; I. D. Naumann" box="[516,894,908,932]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="101 - 133" refId="ref3020" refString="Matthews, R. W., and I. D. Naumann 2002. Descriptions and biology of nine new species of Arpactophilus (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae), with a key to described Australian species. Journal of Hymenoptera Research 11: 101 - 133." type="journal article" year="2002">Matthews and Naumann 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE20FF80FF72B4EAFA78FBFC" blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
Species of subtribe 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FE4DB4EAFD9CFC1C" authorityName="Menke" authorityYear="1989" box="[471,625,940,964]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Spilomenina">Spilomenina</taxonomicName>
(of which 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FD68B4EAFCA8FC1B" authorityName="Pate" authorityYear="1937" box="[754,837,940,963]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE20FF80FD68B4EAFCA8FC1B" box="[754,837,940,963]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Xysma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also a member) are of considerable interest as they include some of the few apoid wasps that exhibit a high degree of social behavior and because adult females are able to spin silk from specialized setae on the sixth tergum, which they use in nest construction (
<bibRefCitation id="B04425A2CE20FF80FEFDB34AFE04FBFC" author="Melo, G. A. R." box="[359,489,1036,1060]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 9" refId="ref3068" refString="Melo, G. A. R. 1997. Silk glands in adult sphecid wasps (Hymenoptera, Sphecidae, Pemphredoninae). Journal of Hymenoptera Research 6: 1 - 9." type="journal article" year="1997">Melo 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B04425A2CE20FF80FE6FB34AFCBDFBFC" author="Serrao, J. E. &amp; L. A. de Oliveira" box="[501,848,1036,1060]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="479 - 486" refId="ref3323" refString="Serrao, J. E., and L. A. de Oliveira. 2000. Notes on the structure of silk glands in sphecid wasps, Microstigmus and Psenulus (Hymenoptera, Sphecidae, Pemphredoninae). Netherlands Journal of Zoology 50: 479 - 486." type="journal article" year="2000">Serrão and de Oliveira 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B04425A2CE20FF80FCC1B34AFB80FBFC" author="Ohl, M. &amp; D. J. Bennett" box="[859,1133,1036,1060]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="145 - 150" refId="ref3102" refString="Ohl, M., and D. J. Bennett. 2009. A new genus and species of apoid wasps from Saxonian amber (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Crabronidae). Denisia 26, zugleich Kataloge der oberosterreichischen Landesmuseen Neue Serie 86: 145 - 150." type="journal article" year="2009">Ohl and Bennett 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B04425A2CE20FF80FBE3B34AFA64FBFC" author="Breitkreuz, L. C. V. &amp; M. Ohl &amp; M. S. Engel" box="[1145,1417,1036,1060]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 66" refId="ref2817" refString="Breitkreuz, L. C. V., M. Ohl, and M. S. Engel. 2016. A review of the New Caledonian Arpactophilus (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae). Zootaxa 4063 (1): 1 - 66." type="journal article" year="2016">Breitkreuz et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46A5853CE20FF80FF72B36AFC69FBBC" blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
These observations are consistent with what little has been published on the nesting behavior of 
<taxonomicName id="13D523D0CE20FF80FF5AB30BFEFEFBBC" authorityName="Pate" authorityYear="1937" box="[192,275,1101,1124]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E6A18441CE20FF80FF5AB30BFEFEFBBC" box="[192,275,1101,1124]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Xysma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation id="B04425A2CE20FF80FEE5B30AFDADFBBC" author="Krombein, K. V." box="[383,576,1100,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="21 - 26" refId="ref2984" refString="Krombein, K. V. 1958. Miscellaneous prey records of solitary wasps. III. (Hymenoptera, Aculeata). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 71: 21 - 26." type="journal article" year="1958">Krombein 1958</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B04425A2CE20FF80FDD1B30AFC9AFBBC" author="Bohart, R. M. &amp; A. S. Menke" box="[587,887,1100,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" refId="ref2781" refString="Bohart, R. M., and A. S. Menke. 1976. Sphecid wasps of the world: a generic revision. University of California Press; Berkeley. 695 p." type="book" year="1976">Bohart and Menke 1976</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
